        <Base:Descriptions>
          <Base:Description type="brief">
             cross-frame chair
          </Base:Description>
          <Base:Description type="examine">
             This cross-frame chair has four main struts, each shaped as an elongated 'S'. The struts which form the feet on one side run up under the seat and emerge to support the arm on the other side. A brass rod forms a central pivot, passing through all four struts, and allowing the chair to be folded. The struts on each side are joined by a board near their feet, and again at their upper ends by the boards forming the arms. Two smaller brass rods also join the sides of the chair, above the fold; a square leather seat is laced to these rods. The chair has no back. The oil-finished oak from which the chair is made is smooth and carefully finished.
          </Base:Description>
          <Base:Description type="glance">
             A folding chair.
          </Base:Description>
          <Base:Description type="look">
             A simple cross-frame chair, with a leather seat.
          </Base:Description>
        </Base:Descriptions>
